Initial thoughts

x1 is row identifier variable and can be dropped date - is month a possible predictor? Or create a season variable? total_volume looks to be sum of 4046, 4225. 4770, total_bags so should be able to be dropped: - check this with alias() to ensure no non-standard data total_bags looks to be sum of small + large + x_large; again check with alias() before dropping. type - check how many distinct region - check how many distinct before deciding what to do with it

distinct(avocados, type)
distinct(avocados, region)

54 distinct regions: going to drop this

# Identify any aliased variables
alias(lm(average_price ~ ., 
         data = avocados_trim))
Model :
average_price ~ total_volume + x4046 + x4225 + x4770 + total_bags + 
    small_bags + large_bags + x_large_bags + type + year + month

No aliased variables? Seems odd when total_bags, total_volume appear to be made up of other variables

avocados %>% 
  mutate(bags = total_bags - small_bags - large_bags  - x_large_bags,
         vol = total_volume - x4046 - x4225 - x4770) %>% 
 filter(bags != 0)

Looks like problem is in rounding of number of decimal places. Just going to drop total_volume, total_bags

avocados_trim <- avocados %>% 
  mutate(month = as.factor(month(date))) %>% 
  select(-c("x1", "date", "total_volume", "total_bags", "region"))

alias(lm(average_price ~ .,
         data = avocados_trim))
Model :
average_price ~ x4046 + x4225 + x4770 + small_bags + large_bags + 
    x_large_bags + type + year + month
